Fife): habitational name from any of several places called Harlaw in Midlothian, Peeblesshire, and Berwickshire, named in Older Scots with <i>hare</i> ‘gray’ + <i>law</i> ‘hill’."],"variants":[{"name":"Herley","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Art, Cormac.","Irish: variant of   Hurley  , probably via   Herlihy  .","English: variant of   Harley   or   Hurley  ."]}]},{"name":"Sybil","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Sybilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sibilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sybille","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Sybil</b> ."]},{"name":"Sibella","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sybil Harley was born in 1300. She had at least 1 daughter with Walter de la Barre. She died in 1338, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1300–1338":"1300–1338","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1337–1421":"1337–1421","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1300":"1300","1421":"1421","about 1337":"umbes 1337","1270":"1270","Whitechurch, Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1300–1338":"1300–1338","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1337–1421":"1337–1421","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1300":"1300","1421":"1421","about 1337":"noin 1337","1270":"1270","Whitechurch, Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1300–1338":"1300–1338","1270–Male":"1270–Décédé","1337–1421":"1337–1421","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1300":"1300","1421":"1421","about 1337":"environ 1337","1270":"1270","Whitechurch, Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Sybil Harley est née en 1300. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Walter de la Barre. Elle est décédée en 1338, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 38 ans."},"de":{"1300–1338":"1300–1338","1270–Male":"1270–Verstorben